#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:270
msgid ""
"Using higher verbosity levels (``-vvv``, ``-vvvv``, ...) is supported, but "
"has no effect in pytest itself at the moment, however some plugins might "
"make use of higher verbosity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:276
msgid "Producing a detailed summary report"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:278
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` flag can be used to display a \"short test summary info\" at the "
"end of the test session, making it easy in large test suites to get a clear "
"picture of all failures, skips, xfails, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:281
msgid "It defaults to ``fE`` to list failures and errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:285
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:287
msgid ""
"# content of test_example.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def error_fixture():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_ok():\n"
"    print(\"ok\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_fail():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_error(error_fixture):\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_skip():\n"
"    pytest.skip(\"skipping this test\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_xfail():\n"
"    pytest.xfail(\"xfailing this test\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"always xfail\")\n"
"def test_xpass():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:323
msgid ""
"$ pytest -ra\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-7.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"SKIPPED [1] test_example.py:22: skipping this test\n"
"XFAIL test_example.py::test_xfail - reason: xfailing this test\n"
"XPASS test_example.py::test_xpass always xfail\n"
"ERROR test_example.py::test_error - assert 0\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:358
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` options accepts a number of characters after it, with ``a`` used "
"above meaning \"all except passes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:361
msgid "Here is the full list of available characters that can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:363
msgid "``f`` - failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:364
msgid "``E`` - error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:365
msgid "``s`` - skipped"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:366
msgid "``x`` - xfailed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:367
msgid "``X`` - xpassed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:368
msgid "``p`` - passed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:369
msgid "``P`` - passed with output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:371
msgid "Special characters for (de)selection of groups:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:373
msgid "``a`` - all except ``pP``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:374
msgid "``A`` - all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:375
msgid ""
"``N`` - none, this can be used to display nothing (since ``fE`` is the "
"default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:377
msgid ""
"More than one character can be used, so for example to only see failed and "
"skipped tests, you can execute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:379
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rfs\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-7.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"SKIPPED [1] test_example.py:22: skipping this test\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:411
msgid ""
"Using ``p`` lists the passing tests, whilst ``P`` adds an extra section "
"\"PASSES\" with those tests that passed but had captured output:"
